Dont Look Down: Navigating Markets Around Cliff Unlocks

Andrew Dyer

19 hours ago   14 min read

Key Insights

  • Cliff unlocks of at least 5% of circulating supply tend to have the most noticeable impact on token relative performance.
  • Relative underperformance of unlock tokens mainly occurs in a window seven days before and seven days after the event.
  • New product launches, sector outperformance, and other catalysts might overwhelm the typical behavior around unlock dates.
  • Highly anticipated large unlocks can have counter-intuitive market reactions.
  • It is difficult for tokens with large monthly cliff unlocks to outperform other altcoins on longer time horizons.

Introduction

Retail market participants have soured on low-float + high FDV projects. However, as ex-Messari analyst Kel notes, the greatest opportunity in crypto is found at the point of highest inflation. Cryptos history is littered with examples of missionaries and believers who hold crypto assets through high inflation periods while mercenary miners and farmers make a quick buck.

With multiple large unlocks looming, paying attention to significant supply events has become increasingly important. This report aims to dive into the price impact of cliff unlocks the periodic release of percentages of the total supply of a token, often to the team, early investors, or DAO treasuries. Linear unlocks are usually released daily in small percentages of circulating supply and might be partially offset by deflation (buyback and burn mechanisms). While the gradual trickle of linear unlocks likely puts a dent in performance over more extended periods, it is much harder to attribute price performance over a given time frame to linear versus cliff unlocks. We will analyze performance across different time frames and tease out potential patterns depending on the market regime.

This report uses Messaris Token Unlocks API to provide a data-driven insight into the historical performances of assets with large cliff unlocks. We cover more than 600 individual cliff unlock events across 41 assets.

The data goes back to January 1, 2023, up to around August 2024. Some of the circulating supply data is sourced from CoinMarketCap. This time frame covers periods when both BTC and altcoins, more broadly, had multi-month up-trends and down-trends, so our data should be representative of different types of market regimes and what we might expect in each.

Entire Dataset Analysis

The chart above shows the distribution of the size of the unlocks (by percentage of circulating supply) across 619 events. Many events are under 2.5% of the circulating supply, which likely means summarizing the entire data set may be a bit noisy.

Average raw returns weeks before and after the unlock events are mildly positive when we look at the whole dataset, except for returns seven days post-event. Why might average returns be positive around supply events besides market drift?

We zoomed into some outlier returns to the upside to understand their context and note that there are extreme moves post-unlocks across a range of unlock percentages and dates. Next, we further investigate why these moves may have happened and in what context for NAVI Protocol, Only1, and Lumerin.

NAVI Protocol is a borrowing/lending market + LSDefi protocol native to SUI. For the NAVX token, there were two prominent cliff unlocks: the one in March 2024 was about 4 million tokens, mainly distributed for airdrops and liquidity incentives (~4% circulating supply), while the one in August 2024 was more substantial and included about 9 million tokens to investors (~7% of circulating supply).

Given that NAVX was listed on some CEXs in February, we would qualify the first vertical move as a new listing pump trade rather than having anything to do with the weekly incentive airdrop. Similar moves happened across recently listed assets like ONDO, ZETA, PIXEL, and others around that time. The second aggressive post-unlock move came shortly after a 30% down day when BTC fell into the high 40s. In the following days, the rapid mean-reversion in the alt market (and BTC) overwhelmed additional supply in this case.

Only1 is a decentralized platform for adult content creators on Solana. The protocol had 14.4 million LIKE tokens unlocked primarily to Venture backers and the community. However, at prices in early 2023, this was less than $75,000. After falling more than 95% from its Kucoin listing high in 2021, it is not surprising for a micro-cap with a market cap of less than $10 million) to move aggressively to the upside unlock or no. The later unlocks on the chart were regular sub-2% of circulating supply unlocks issued monthly for the past year. They occurred during a more extended period in which SOL and projects on SOL were broadly outperforming the rest of the market (ex: JUP, JTO, SHDW, WHALES, etc).

Lumerin runs a hashpower marketplace that allows buying, selling, and mining of Bitcoin with remotely acquired hashpower. They also have a decentralized AI data routing product. Lumerin (LMR) had monthly cliff unlocks of almost 30 million tokens for most of 2023 and the first quarter of 2024. In 2023, these were large percentages of circulating supply (more than 5-10%), although the dollar values were fairly small. In October 2023, LMR had numerous posts from some smaller influencer accounts on Twitter, a few weeks after their hash-power marketplace launched which may have been the reason for its outperformance. The February 2024 move was most likely after the market interpreted Lumerins partnership with AI protocol Morpheus as bullish and/or was treating LMR as a proxy play for Morpheus before it launched, given the protocol would receive some MOR allocation for being a compute provider.

Overall, context around these dates is essential as there are distinctive factors that may cause unlock events to be bullish: new listings, market-wide mean reversion after large drawdowns, recent product launches or upcoming catalysts, sector or ecosystem outperformance, airdrop incentives, or broader periods of risk-on sentiment.

Now that we have examined some situations where the data may be skewed to the upside by outliers, lets remove the effect of the market beta by subtracting BTC returns (excess returns). We will look at median returns to get a less distorted view of the effect.

We observe that median excess returns are decisively negative, meaning the median token return underperformed BTC both before and after the event. This underperformance extends for a month around the event and is fairly symmetrical the market tends to front-run the event but also continues to sell off versus BTC afterward.

Large Unlocks Only

Cliff unlocks that are not particularly large can be overwhelmed by other market forces pre and post-event. Therefore, we next examine unlocks that are at least 5% of the circulating supply at the unlock date as these should have a more pronounced impact on price, all else equal.

We have about 100 of these events in the dataset, and observe a more dramatic underperformance without as many outliers to the upside.

Average excess returns are more negative than for the whole dataset. In the case of large unlocks, it also seems that the market front runs the event more heavily, as the returns before and after are more asymmetric. However, these tokens still underperform BTC by multiple percentage points days after the event.

Interestingly, getting more granular closer to the day of the event implies that recipients of unlocks do not immediately sell their tokens, nor does the market hedge aggressively the day before as indicated by flat to positive returns versus BTC:

Given that alts have broadly underperformed BTC in recent months, lets view performance relative to TOTAL3 - the total crypto market capitalization excluding BTC and ETH - around these dates. This will give us a view of performance versus altcoins more broadly.

Tokens across these 100 events underperformed not only against BTC but also vs. the average altcoin around these events. This analysis obviously ignores execution and funding costs, liquidity, and short availability, but is nevertheless still informative.

Above, we observe the effect of the unlock in the average price path of a token with a cliff unlock as compared to BTC and TOTAL3, before and after the event. Although taking an average price path (normalized) across 100 events is a bit noisy, the unlock effect is evident when zooming in on the week before and after the event, with clear underperformance versus the rest of the market.

If we plot the average return 7 days prior to the unlock bucketed by unlock size we see a decent linear relationship; generally, the bigger the unlock, the bigger the underperformance.

While our dataset is limited, the results imply an underlying economic rationale:

  • The market starts to price in the additional supply fairly close to the event.
  • Unlock recipients either take a few days to sell their supply (if they sell at all) and/or the market continues to price in the additional supply days afterward.
  • Then the token largely resumes its prior correlation to the broader market.
  • Lastly, the relative underperformance of the token seems to scale with the size of the unlock.

Case Studies

It is useful to dissect individual cases where unlocks are frequent and heavily scrutinized. In this section, we will study dYdX and AltLayer + ZetaChain.

DYDX When Trades Become Obvious, Run the Other Way

DYDXs history is particularly illustrative of the winding paths markets can take around these events. Back in January 2023, traders were focused on a 150 million token unlock scheduled for February 2, 2023. This would be a massive increase in circulating supply from around 200 million tokens. Posts on Twitter largely thought this would be universally bearish long-term, even though there might be a short-term trade to the upside.

How did the market react in anticipation closer to the event? It first rallied 71% off the lows. Then, towards the end of January, the dYdX Foundation issued a post pushing back the unlock date to December 1, 2023; DYDX proceeded to rally another 139% in the days afterward.

The token ultimately retraced more than 50% of these moves and did not move much for the rest of the year. When the massive unlock finally happened at the end of 2023, the market proceeded to drive DYDX up more than 140% from the end of October to the middle of November.

This was also being done on positive funding, implying there was not any sort of short squeeze happening. The token price proceeded not to move too drastically days around the event relative to where it started; this was certainly counter-intuitive on a first-order. However, highly anticipated events often invite short-term predatory behavior to take advantage of those positioning with first-order thinking.

Although no meaningful underperformance can be observed from the plain vanilla price chart, studying the relative performance of dYdX draws a different picture. The release of huge chunks of supply (more than 5% of circulating supply each month in DYDXs case) over a one-year period does show up in relative underperformance, as can be seen from the DYDX/TOTAL3 chart. It even displays the typical relative underperformance versus BTC in the 14-day windows around most of its cliff unlocks this year.

ZETA + ALT Novelty Versus Supply

AltLayer and ZetaChain are newer infrastructure protocols with token generation events earlier this year. While there were no changes in vesting schedules or extreme moves observable around the events, they both had significant monthly supply events over the past year.

ZETA has around 44 million tokens unlocking the first of every month in the coming months, which at around 343 million tokens in circulating supply today, is more than 12%. Going back the past five months, these regular 44 million unlocks were even larger portions of the circulating supply. ZETAs underperformance versus the broader market since listing is evident. Given that unlocks are less than 50% complete, ZETA faces continued supply headwinds for the foreseeable future.

Similarly, AltLayer has released 183 million tokens every month since March of this year. While this now represents almost 8% of their circulating supply (at 2.3 billion tokens currently), these were also larger portions of supply going back to the prior months. This past July saw an even bigger 684 million unlock, with the vast majority going to the team, investors, and advisors the relative underperformance versus BTC is evident in the chart annotations.

Thus far, there has been a brief window when newer tokens like these can capture enough mindshare or attract fast money to outperform other alts more broadly. ALT and ZETA had short periods post-listing where they outperformed TOTAL3, but the relative underperformance versus the rest of the market still shows up in the two-week window around large unlock events. The underperformance does not happen every single time there certainly will be moments when the narratives any of these coins are associated with like modularity or chain abstraction will get outsized attention over a period. But on average, it is difficult to outperform BTC (and other alts with no unlocks) when major portions of supply hit the market each month.

Conclusion

Datasets like these can always be biased through universe selection and the periods we put under a microscope. However, we have seen some evidence of a limited window (-/+ 7 days) around these events where underperformance rears its head. We also see plenty of scenarios where temporary demand may overwhelm the effect: new product launches, centralized exchange listings, recent sector outperformance, low liquidity, and even vesting schedule changes. Our analysis shows that the most significant impact has been when the unlock size is substantial enough more than 5-10% of circulating supply and there are no upcoming catalysts or much attention around the token in general.

Unlocks and supply changes have become more critical factors in the Keynesian beauty contest of crypto markets. When other investors and traders see a recently listed token that only has 25% of its supply in circulation, with plenty of cliff unlocks in the coming months, will they think it is attractive to anyone else looking at it? In the non-meme space, novelty and narratives will only get you so far in a market that is growing more and more discerning. Participants should pay more attention to these events, just as teams should be more deliberate about the size and pace of their vesting schedules.
